, but under the impact of the 1905 Revolution they later also subscribed to current radical political ideas. The eventual collision between these dreams and tsarist reality generated enormous intellectual turbulence and the need for substitutes. Not least psychoanalysis came to the rescue of these stranded dreamers. The present collection of essays is intended for readers interested in Russian literature or the early history of Eastern European offshoots of psychoanalysis.  afunded by National Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Program  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aSymbolism (Literary movement)zRussiaxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh2 aNational Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Programefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015z978311068814640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781618116963zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781618116963zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781618116963/original  a978-3-11-068814-6 Academic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015c2008d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA